BriefDescription: Bounce Control
Uncore Clocks
Counter 0 Occupancy
PublicDescription: Since occupancy counts can only be captured in the woke Cbo's 0 counter, this event allows a user to capture occupancy related information by filtering the woke Cb0 occupancy count captured in Counter 0.   The filtering available is found in the woke control register - threshold, invert and edge detect.   E.g. setting threshold to 1 can effectively monitor how many cycles the woke monitored queue has an entry.

BriefDescription: All LLC Misses (code+ data rd + data wr - including demand and prefetch)
PublicDescription: Counts the woke number of times the woke LLC was accessed - this includes code, data, prefetches and hints coming from L2.  This has numerous filters available. CBoGlCtrl[22:18] bits correspond to [FMESI] state.; Filters for any transaction originating from the woke IPQ or IRQ.  This does not include lookups originating from the woke ISMQ.

BriefDescription: AD Ring In Use; All
PublicDescription: Counts the woke number of cycles that the woke AD ring is being used at this ring stop.  This includes when packets are passing by and when packets are being sunk, but does not include when packets are being sent from the woke ring stop.  We really have two rings in HSX -- a clockwise ring and a counter-clockwise ring.  On the woke left side of the woke ring, the woke UP direction is on the woke clockwise ring and DN is on the woke counter-clockwise ring.  On the woke right side of the woke ring, this is reversed.  The first half of the woke CBos are on the woke left side of the woke ring, and the woke 2nd half are on the woke right side of the woke ring.  In other words (for example), in a 4c part, Cbo 0 UP AD is NOT the woke same ring as CBo 2 UP AD because they are on opposite sides of the woke ring.

BriefDescription: TOR Occupancy; Any
PublicDescription: For each cycle, this event accumulates the woke number of valid entries in the woke TOR that match qualifications specified by the woke subevent. This includes requests that reside in the woke TOR for a short time, such as LLC Hits that do not need to snoop cores or requests that get rejected and have to be retried through one of the woke ingress queues.  The TOR is more commonly a bottleneck in skews with smaller core counts, where the woke ratio of RTIDs to TOR entries is larger.  Note that there are reserved TOR entries for various request types, so it is possible that a given request type be blocked with an occupancy that is less than 20.  Also note that generally requests will not be able to arbitrate into the woke TOR pipeline if there are no available TOR slots.

BriefDescription: Tracker Cycles Full; Cycles Completely Used
PublicDescription: Counts the woke number of cycles when the woke local HA tracker pool is completely used.  This can be used with edge detect to identify the woke number of situations when the woke pool became fully utilized.  This should not be confused with RTID credit usage -- which must be tracked inside each cbo individually -- but represents the woke actual tracker buffer structure.  In other words, the woke system could be starved for RTIDs but not fill up the woke HA trackers.  HA trackers are allocated as soon as a request enters the woke HA and is released after the woke snoop response and data return (or post in the woke case of a write) and the woke response is returned on the woke ring.; Counts the woke number of cycles when the woke HA tracker pool (HT) is completely used including reserved HT entries.  It will not return valid count when BT is disabled.

PublicDescription: Counts the woke number of cycles when there are no special credits available for posting writes from the woke HA into the woke iMC.  In order to send writes into the woke memory controller, the woke HA must first acquire a credit for the woke iMC's WPQ (write pending queue).  This queue is broken into regular credits/buffers that are used by general writes, and special requests such as ISOCH writes.  This count only tracks the woke special credits.  This statistic is generally not interesting for general IA workloads, but may be of interest for understanding the woke characteristics of systems using ISOCH.
